WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.680
I'm here to talk about an exceedingly low tech, very norm core topic, which is how to

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:09.800
name files.

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:10.800
My name is Jenny Bryan.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:15.960
I'm a software engineer at Posit, formerly known as RStudio.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:23.360
I work on a team that maintains a bunch of open source R packages known as the Tidyverse.

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:30.080
While I was procrastinating on preparing this talk, I watched the latest Jason Bourne movie,

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:36.000
which actually has this great little bit of filename porn within it.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.320
These filenames aren't exactly my style, but I have to say there's a lot of good stuff

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.860
going on here with these filenames.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:52.580
My overall goal is to inspire you to have a filename convention, even if it differs

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:54.320
from mine.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:59.959
It will eliminate a lot of irritating micro decisions and make your filenames easier to

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:03.540
compute on downstream.

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:06.660
Here's a bit of filename before versus after.

00:01:06.660 --> 00:01:12.699
Up top, the before filenames are problematic because they're generic or mysterious or they

00:01:12.699 --> 00:01:19.800
contain challenging characters, whereas the after filenames down below are easy to read

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:23.779
and easy to compute on.

00:01:23.779 --> 00:01:28.900
You want a system that gives you filenames that are machine readable, human readable,

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:34.379
and sorted in a way that's useful to you.

00:01:34.379 --> 00:01:39.739
The most basic thing you might want to do is use globbing to isolate files that match

00:01:39.739 --> 00:01:42.360
a simple pattern.

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:48.500
A more sophisticated operation that comes up is the need to extract data from a filename

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:51.099
using a regular expression.

00:01:51.099 --> 00:01:57.139
I'm showing a bit of R code that turns a bunch of filenames into a data frame, and I assume

00:01:57.139 --> 00:02:00.059
you can do this in your preferred language.

00:02:00.059 --> 00:02:06.820
I use the underscore to delimit fields and the hyphen to separate words within fields.

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:12.899
I think it has to be this way because a very common field is a date and a hyphen is how

00:02:12.899 --> 00:02:17.919
we separate year from month from day.

00:02:17.919 --> 00:02:25.380
The overall guiding principle is to make things easy for future you.

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:31.919
So a machine readable filename is easy to target with glob patterns and regular expressions,

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:37.800
and it's going to have a very intentional use of delimiters.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:43.039
Let's say you drop in on a project at 3 a.m. before a deadline.

00:02:43.039 --> 00:02:46.839
Which set of filenames are you hoping to see?

00:02:46.839 --> 00:02:52.839
I think it's the ones on the right because they embrace the slug.

00:02:52.839 --> 00:02:57.639
We're going to borrow this term from the world of the web, which has the idea that a good

00:02:57.639 --> 00:03:03.199
URL indicates something about the page content.

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:10.320
So human readable filenames make it easy for humans to infer what the content or the purpose

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:14.759
of a file is based on its name.

00:03:14.759 --> 00:03:21.240
Here are two examples of useful sort order, logical and chronological.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:29.520
On the left are files from a small data analysis pipeline that basically sort in order of execution.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:35.880
On the right are some ad hoc housekeeping scripts where I record the date I did a little

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:38.880
piece of work.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:45.080
I want to put in a plug for left padding numbers so that you don't end up in the sad situation

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:53.600
you see up top where the last script in a pipeline appears before the first script.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.440
Left padding is going to fix this problem for you.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:02.960
I live in Canada now but I was born in the U.S. so I'm going to apologize on behalf of

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:09.839
that nation for the horrible things that Americans do with dates.

00:04:09.839 --> 00:04:17.519
In any context that is remotely data oriented, all dates should follow the ISO 8601 standard

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:22.040
where we have year, month, day.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:24.200
That is all.

00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:29.600
So by default, you know you're going to see your files in alpha numeric order.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:33.640
You should just resign yourself to that and plan accordingly.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:39.119
So we want to see dates or a left padded number at the beginning followed by a highly

00:04:39.119 --> 00:04:42.119
informative slug.

00:04:42.119 --> 00:04:47.519
I hope this helps you develop a file naming scheme that works for you.

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:52.679
These slides and some other resources are available at the short link you see here and

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:57.799
I look forward to seeing more of you on Twitter or GitHub or Mastodon.

00:04:57.799 --> 00:04:58.959
Thanks and bye bye.

